A minimal design is to make the function do exactly one thing and make that explicit in both name and contract.

```ts
function add(a: number, b: number): number {
  return a + b;
}
```

Design constraints:
- Accept exactly two numeric inputs.
- Return only their sum.
- Do not handle subtraction, multiplication, parsing, validation, or formatting.
- Fail fast if your language/runtime requires type checks.

If you want a slightly more defensive version:

```ts
function add(a: number, b: number): number {
  if (!Number.isFinite(a) || !Number.isFinite(b)) {
    throw new Error("add expects two finite numbers");
  }
  return a + b;
}
```

If you want, I can also propose the same design in a specific language or in OOP/API form.

